observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management: 

Require the BAC Secretariat to:

Submit final APP and its printout copy in prescribed forms received by GPPB and posted in GPPB website as well as minutes of Bid Evaluation for the aforementioned procurement activities;

Submit minutes of pre-procurement conference relative to procurement on Support to Farmers - Hybrid Yellow Assistance with an ABC of ₱2,100,000.00;

Hold pre-procurement conference prior to the date of first posting of Invitation to Bid in the succeeding transactions;

Issue a notification letter to all bidders who have submitted their bid proposal in the succeeding procurement activities;

Observe the prescribed periods in the posting of NOA, NTP and Approved Contract in the website of PhilGEPS; and

Ensure that the certifications on the advertisement of ITB and posting of NOA, Contract Agreement and NTP at conspicuous places in the premises of the agency are duly supported with pictures/evidence.



Instruct the BAC and TWG to strictly observe the guidelines in the conduct and preparation of PQER to include the result of verification and validation of all the statements made and documents submitted by the winning bidder to establish properly the eligibility of the participating bidders.



Direct the BAC to:

Ensure the compliance of winning bidders in the posting of surety bonds callable upon demand as performance securities duly certified by the Insurance Commission before the awarding and signing of the contract;


Ensure that the validity of the performance bond posted by the winning bidders would cover the defects liability period equivalent to one year from project completion up to final acceptance of the project; the disbursing officer.

Keep abreast with the relevant GPPB issuances to be updated with the new policies and guidelines regarding procurement processes.

We recommended that Management:

Provide a stockroom for the supplies and materials of the  Municipality to properly monitor and control the inventoriable items;

Accountant to analyze and Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to conduct a physical count of inventories semi-annually and the subsequent report thereon be submitted to the Audit Team;



Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to monitor and control the inventory of supplies and materials through issuance of RIS and maintenance of stock cards for supplies; and



Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to consolidate weekly the RIS issued and facilitate the preparation of SSMI which will be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the consumption and/or distribution in the appropriate expense accounts.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations and made additional recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
(a) require the Acting-Municipal Accountant to (i) ensure that all purchases of supplies and materials are recorded under the proper inventory account; (ii) prepare supplies ledger cards for delivered items as called for in the above-quoted regulation; and (ii) ensure complete documentation in reference to COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and take emphasis on the noted incomplete documentation in item 2.20 of this report prior to payment of claims;
(b) inform the BAC to examine noted deviations in Item 2.20, for future similar transactions, adhere closely with the requirements of the procurement law, preceding to payment thereof;
(c) direct the HRMO to review the staffing positions for the General Services Officer, and provide additional manpower, if warranted and budget permits to aid in the compliance of the above observation on supplies management;
(d) Reconstitute the inventory committee that will be active in the requisite conduct of semestral inventory of supplies in accordance with the Manual; and
(e) instruct the GSO to (i) consolidate the purchase requests of all departments and make an effort to procure directly from the PS-DBM all anticipated common-use supplies and resort to local suppliers only upon unavailability of supplies needed; (ii) ensure the completeness of the supplies records such as the RIS, AIR and Stock Cards to provide accurate data to reports sourced therein.

We reiterated and supplemented our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
(a) implement the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), recognition of PPE found at the station, and disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as laid out in COA Circular 2020-006;
(b) reconstitute an Inventory Committee, including at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Department of the LGU in pursuance to item 5.2. of COA Circular 2020-006 who will spearhead the conduct of complete physical count of all the LGU’s properties and eventual compliance with the required annual submission of RPCPPE;
(c) require the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to (i) exert efforts to prepare complete Property Cards and Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aiming for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered; (ii) work coordinately with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer on the inventory of all local road projects with complete description and cost segregation of road components to ensure proper recording and control of the assets and prepare the respective Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Local Road Network Property Card; and (iii) cause the tracing of the initial recognition of all PPE to comply with the preparation and maintenance of Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards;
(d) enjoin the Acting-Municipal Accountant, GSO, and Municipal Engineer to attend training/s relative to LRAMM by the DILG, adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein, and comply with the requirements thereof in reporting as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
(e) direct the GSO to coordinate with the LTO to check on the status of the application for government plates and consequent compliance with the mandatory registration of all owned vehicles with government red plates; and
(f) instruct the Acting-Municipal Accountant to investigate the cause of the error in recording of CIP account and prepare the appropriate adjusting journal entries, if warranted, to correct the misstatements of the affected accounts to reflect the accurate value of PPE in the financial statements.

We reiterated and supplemented our prior year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the Acting Municipal Accountant to:
(a) continue with the preparation of subsidiary ledgers for upcoming fund transfers;
(b) track the cause of the discrepancy between the SL vis-a-vis the GL of the “Due to NGAs” and “Due to LGUs” accounts and prepare the necessary subsidiary ledgers;
(c) in coordination with the former and current BAC Chairman, submit lacking documents on contracts discussed in item 4.10.7. of this Report; and
(d) look into the other deficiencies noted in item 4.10.8. to avert recurrence thereof in future similar transactions; and
(e) effect the necessary entry in the GF to recognize the assets derecognized in the TF;

We reiterated and made supplemental audit recommendations thereof and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
(a) HRMO to continuously post the vacant positions on the appropriate website to encourage applicants to fill the mandatory positions in the MDRMMO Office;
(b) LDRRMO together with the LDRRMC, to (i) prepare and submit annually the LDRRMFIP in the required format in reference to COA Circular 2012-002, inclusive of the plan relative to the unexpended balance of the fund for the current year and the trust fund for DRRM; (ii) regularly monitor implementation thereof to avoid non-attainment of the target objectives of the fund; and (iii) follow the PPAs embodied in the 3-year plan, otherwise, the proposed changes should be accompanied with adequate recommendation and approval of the LDRRMC and Sangguniang Bayan and LCE, respectively;
(c) Acting-Municipal Accountant to (i) look into the noted common observations in item 6.26 of this report for consideration on future similar disbursements in conformance with the processes and documentary requirements stated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 prior to payment; (ii) prepare necessary entries to reflect the transfer of the unexpended balance of the fund to the Special Trust Fund account; and (iii) provide adequate disclosures as required in the earlier mentioned Circulars; and
(d) Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the actual transfer of the unexpended balance of the DRRMF to the trust fund account in accordance with the above-cited Circular.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

enforce the immediate liquidation and/or refund of the unliquidated cash advances;

refrain from granting additional cash advance to officials and employees with outstanding advances until previous cash advances are fully settled /liquidated; and

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require:

the MDRRMO to:

utilize the LDRRMF in accordance with the approved LDRRMFIP in relation to finding a;

the Municipal Accountant to:

present accurate data in the Report on the Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in relation to finding c;

attach a copy of ICS upon issuance thereof to end-users in relation to finding d;

3.7 We reiterated the previous year’s audit recommendations that Management:

3.7.1 Instruct the end-users to prepare the RIS for every request in the issuance of supplies and semi-expendable properties to facilitate the preparation of SSMI and RSPI by the Municipal Treasurer;

3.7.2 Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
3.7.2.1 Maintain stock cards, prepare the SSMI and complete the physical inventory of supplies for the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and submit the said inventory report to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
3.7.2.2 Prepare and maintain the required forms, registries and reports for semi-expendable properties and use the prescribed numbering structure in assigning a separate ICS control number for low-valued items and high-valued items to strengthen the controls and safeguards over the semi-expendable properties; and

3.7.3 Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the Supplies Ledger Cards per stock number for delivered supplies and Semi-expendable Property Ledger Cards for each class of semi-expendable property and ensure that semi-expendable properties are recorded in their appropriate expense account.

We recommended that Management:
a. Establish an Inventory Committee, require the conduct of an annual inventory-taking of all PPE and submit the RPCPPE in the prescribed form based on the complete and actual physical count conducted;
b. Require the GSO-Designate and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the property records for all PPE and undertake the required reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records thereafter;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify items with individual costs below ₱50,000.00 to the appropriate semi-expendable property inventory accounts in accordance with Section 3.3 of COA Circular No. 2024-006; and
d. Facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances through the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that Management:
a. Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding CAs, especially from all AOs and employees still connected with the LGU. Immediately coordinate with the concerned AOs to secure and submit copies of transmittal letters duly received by the COA ICFAU;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the grant, utilization and liquidation of CAs and ensure that no additional CA is granted unless the previous CA is fully liquidated or properly accounted for, in order to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CAs;
c. Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding CAs and conduct verification, analysis and validation to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
d. Continue to strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CAs.

We recommended that Management:
a. Conduct an in-depth verification of the Due to BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth accounts, perform reconciliation between the SLs and the Schedules of Remittances, make necessary adjustments in the books to reflect accurate balances and remit immediately all overdue obligations to prevent further accumulation and avoid potential penalties, if warranted, and;
b. Evaluate the current system of withholding and remitting taxes, premiums, contributions and other deductions to prevent under or over remittance thereof.

We recommended that Management:
a. Maximize the utilization of the 20 percent DF by ensuring the immediate implementation of the identified PPAs;
b. Direct the Municipal Engineer to: i) ensure the completeness and accuracy of the Consolidated Report on Government PPAs; ii) ensure that tarpaulin signboards for each project are installed or posted at the project site as soon as the award has been made, and the cost of which must be included in the project cost; and iii) explain why the Contract for the Repair of Multi-purpose Hall in San Juan was executed a year after the issuance of NOA and why the additional works and materials for the same project was separately procured;
c. Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to exercise stricter scrutiny in the preparation and evaluation of bidding documents, conduct of procurement activities and ensure compliance with the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and other relevant procurement guidelines. Further, require the submission of complete and accurate documentary requirements on procurement transactions pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to require the attachment of photos of installed project signboards at the project site in processing related payments.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant and MDRRMO to exert efforts in identifying the details of unreconciled balances, update their respective books and records accordingly and reconcile any discrepancies thereafter;
b. Direct the MDRRMO to present the STF as a consolidated amount in the LDRRMF Utilization Report, without subdividing into QRF and MF–MOOE, and indicate funding sources by year of transfer in LDRRMFIP to support accurate tracking and effective monitoring of unutilized balances;
c. Stop the incurrence of non-allowable administrative and operating charges in the LDRRMF. Also, require the MDRRMO to submit a justification/legal basis to support disbursements of the LDRRMF amounting to ₱841,239.70; and
d. Enjoin the LDRRM Office to closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF, including those under the STF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO)/GFPS Focal Person to promptly coordinate with the DILG Provincial Office to obtain the required Certification of Review and Endorsement for the submitted GPB and to ensure that all future GPB submissions are accompanied by the required certification;
b. Instruct the MSWDO/GFPS Focal Person, in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), to facilitate the gathering of data and information needed for the creation of an updated and well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs, as well as in the policy formulation, in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns;
c. Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and training on gender and development to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GPB; and
d. Ensure that the PPAs charged to GAD fund are only those that would address the identified gender issues in the locality. The gender issues must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex-disaggregated data and gender analysis results.

6.5 We recommended that the OIC – Municipal Accountant, in collaboration with the Municipal Treasurer, affirmed to immediately initiate the process of refunding all unutilized funds to the Source Agencies and develop a clear timeline and action plan for the refund process, ensuring timely completion;
6.6 Furthermore, we recommended and the OIC – Municipal Accountant agreed to make all efforts to maintain all MOAs. If the MOAs cannot be found, the Municipality should work with the Source Agency to create a new MOA, or to officially terminate the agreement and refund the same amount; and
6.7 Establish a system for regular monitoring and review of project fund utilization to ensure that all project-related documentation, including MOAs, is properly maintained and readily accessible preventing the accumulation of unutilized funds in the future.

We recommended and the Management agreed, that the Municipal Mayor and the Job Order personnel execute a Job Order contract instead of an office order;
We also recommended and the Management agreed, that the Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer ensure that travel allowances are paid only to JO personnel whose contracts explicitly authorize to travel;
We further recommended and the Management agreed, that the Municipal Mayor issue an Executive Order establishing internal policies, guidelines, and limitations on travel claims for JO personnel; and
Lastly, we recommended and the Management agreed, that the Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the travel claims of JO personnel to ensure they are properly approved by the authorized official and supported by the required certifications and other necessary documents before processing payment.

We recommended and the Management agreed, the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
Reconcile the discrepancies totaling ₱2,805,490.40 between the amount withheld and the amount remitted for the current year;
Reconcile the previous years’ net outstanding balance of ₱814,843.55;
Remit immediately the identified/reconciled balance of Due to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, PhilHealth and GOCCs accounts as at December 31, 2024; and
Effect the necessary accounting entries based on the result of reconciliation.

We recommended that Management:
a. Provide a stockroom for the supplies and materials of the LGU to properly monitor and control the stockroom inventoriable items; 
b. Accountant to analyse and Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to conduct a physical count of inventories semi-annually and the subsequent report for CY 2023 thereon be submitted to the Audit Team; 
c. Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to monitor and control the inventory of supplies and materials through issuance of RIS and maintenance of stock cards for supplies; and 
d. Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to consolidate weekly the RIS issued and facilitate the preparation of SSMI which will be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the consumption and/or distribution in the appropriate expense accounts.

We reiterated and supplemented our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

reconstitute an Inventory Committee, including at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Department of the LGU in pursuance to item 5.2. of COA Circular 2020-006 who will spearhead the conduct of complete physical count of all the LGU’s properties;

require the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to exert efforts to prepare the Property Cards and Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Cards, respectively, starting with the current year’s acquisition and recent years’ acquisitions and aiming for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered;

require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to (i) work coordinately with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer on the inventory of all local road projects with complete description and cost segregation of road components to ensure proper recording and control of the assets and prepare the respective Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Local Road Network Property Card; and (ii) cause the tracing of the initial recognition of all PPE to comply with the preparation and maintenance of Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards;

enjoin the Acting-Municipal Accountant, GSO and Municipal Engineer to attend training/s relative to LRAMM by the DILG, adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and comply with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008; and

instruct the Acting-Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare the appropriate adjusting journal entries, if warranted, to correct the misstatements of the affected accounts. Henceforth, ensure that costs of major repairs, rehabilitation, improvement, and construction of infrastructure assets are capitalized or recognized as property, plant and equipment, in accordance with International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) No. 17 and related rules on asset recognition; and (ii) recognize depreciation using a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year and asset impairment to reflect the accurate value of PPE in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive requires the:

Municipal Treasurer to:

Pay the LGU the amount of ₱2,400.00 as replenishment for the deduction made against its deposits with the bank;

We recommended that Management to:

instruct the GSO to notify the office of the Auditor within twenty-four (24) hours from acceptance, the time, date and place of delivery to give the AT ample time in the conduct of inspection;

instruct the GSO Designate and the Inspection Officer to properly fill-out the AIR and submit the same within the prescribed period, and;

to submit scanned copy of notification of delivery including the supporting documents to AT via e-mail considering the risks of COVID-19 and travel time from the LGU to Provincial Satellite Auditing Office (PSAO) and vice-versa

We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Treasurer to:

 Submit all missing disbursement vouchers to the accounting office for proper recording in the books of the LGU;

Prepare the RCI containing all checks issued during the period and submit this to the Accounting Office together with corresponding DVs;

Ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the DVs before the paid transactions are transmitted to the accounting office; and

Observe the 90-day period within which to submit the missing DVs before suspensions mature into disallowance.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant prepare and record JEV upon receipt of DVs and supporting documents to adjust and correct balances of the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Submit the lacking supporting documents enumerated, especially the Official Receipts and the original Delivery Receipts to the Office of the Auditor;

Direct the Supply Officer to conduct pre-repair evaluation/inspection and post-repair evaluation/inspection of all its government vehicles subjected to repairs;

Require that the Report of Waste Material be prepared by the Supply Officer and approved by the Local Chief Executive; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to always ensure that future payments for repair and maintenance of vehicles are processed with complete and appropriate supporting documents pursuant to Section 9.1.3.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Create an Inventory Committee who will conduct a systematic and complete physical count of PPE in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and ensure timely submission of RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;

Require the Accountant to work back and review the entries in the PPE Ledgers with unreconciled balances and make the necessary adjusting entries on the affected accounts; and

Consider designating a GSO, not from any department with demanding responsibility, who will discharge on a full-time basis the procurement and issuance of supplies and property, maintain updated Property Cards per category on all Agency’s assets as recorded in the list of PPEs of accounting records, and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE; 

For missing PPE items which can no longer be found/located despite great effort, we recommended that Management strictly follow the guidelines of Section 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items of government agencies.

