observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Require the GSO-Designate and the Municipal Assessor to exert effort in the retrieval of land titles and other necessary documents as basis to establish ownership and determine proper valuation;

Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the Municipal Government of Mandaon to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third-party claims;

Make representations with the Land Registration Authority or Registry of Deeds to confirm the ownership of all land properties covered by the Tax Declaration on hand and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly account all the land properties of the Municipality using the cost or fair value and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in accordance with IPSAS 17 or any other applicable accounting standard; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to update religiously the cash books and the data reflected be preferably considered in the preparation of the BRS to ensure that any reconciling items will be accordingly adjusted.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursements for repairs made by the Municipality are supported with complete and appropriate documentation as prescribed in Section 9.1.3.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and Section 362 Volume I of GAAM;

Pre-repair Evaluation Reports and the Post-inspection Reports relative to the above-mentioned transactions; 

Require that Certificates of Acceptance and RWMs be prepared by the Supply Officer/GSO-Designate and approved by the Local Chief Executive, in case of major repairs and if the repairs need replacement; and

Direct the BAC and other concerned officers to revisit the provisions of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, specifically in employing different alternative modes of procurement and their procedures, to ensure its compliance at all times.

We recommended that Management submit to the Office of the Auditor the following documents to support the transactions amounting to ₱5,960,924.04:

For the procurement of food packs:
	i. Program of Work/Detailed Plans/activity design;
	ii. Contract/s or purchase orders with specification/details of the articles involved in the procurement, and the date and place of the delivery;
	iii. Attendance sheets/Distribution Sheets; and
	iv. Fully accomplished Inspection and Acceptance Reports and Delivery Receipts.

For the procurement of medicines and medical supplies;
	i. Properly signed and accomplished Purchase Order, RIS, Inspection and Acceptance Reports, Delivery Receipts; and
	ii. The certification from the manufacturer that the supplier is an authorized distributor/dealer of the products/items, for the procurement of medicines.

We also recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant ensure that: a) all disbursements made by the Municipality are supported with complete documentation as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Circular No. 2009-001; and b) the attached documents are properly signed and accomplished in compliance with the applicable laws and regulations to ascertain the validity, legality and propriety of every transaction made by the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Strictly observe the rules and regulation relative to the preparation of the monthly BRS and submit the same to COA within the prescribed period;

Regularly obtain copies of Bank Statements from the bank, or make continuous reminder or follow up with the bank if the same are not obtained. If possible, enroll in the online access/services of DBP in order to obtain soft copies of monthly bank statements for all the funds of the LGU;

Prepare/update the Subsidiary Ledger Cards per bank accounts for all the funds; and

Regular coordination between the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer must be made in order that reconciling cash balances in the respective books and records will be adjusted timely and accordingly.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly comply with the laws, rules and regulation relative to the granting, liquidation and monitoring of cash advances;

Require the Accountant to devise means or procedure to strengthen the internal control with respect to granting and monitoring of cash advances in order that the data and documents of previous cash advances will not be lost. Ensure that the Cash Advance of retiring, resigning or transferring employee is first settled before approving the clearance from money and property accountability; 

Refrain from granting additional cash advances if the previous cash advance has not been fully settled or liquidated;

Send demand letters to erring Accountable Officers and Employees requiring them to immediately settle and/or refund the remaining cash advance, otherwise, withhold the salaries of those who neglectfully or intentionally fail to settle their cash advances within the prescribed period after demand;

Evaluate individually the probability of collection of outstanding cash advances especially those Dormant Accounts and send request for write off to COA in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

Enforce appropriate legal action in order to recover/ settle the unliquidated Cash Advances of liable persons and employees and set as an example to those erring officials and employees that their negligence or failure to liquidate cash advances within the prescribed period has a corresponding adverse consequence.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require a.) The mdrrmo to utilize the LDRRMF in accordance with the approved LDRRMFIP in relation to finding a;                                           b.) the Municipal Accountant to:                     ;                                                      1.) present accurate data in the Report on the Sources and Utilization of DRRMF in relation to finding c;                                                                             2.) attach a copy of ICS upon issuance thereof to end-users in relation to finding d; 
(3) record procured items which did not meet the capitalization threshold in its appropriate Inventory accounts
c.) the MBO to:
(40) support any changes in the current year LDRRMFIP with augmentation, realignment or supplemental budget, if any, in relation to finding a;
(41) prepare and maintain separate RAAOs for QRF, MOOE and CO in relation to finding b; and
(42) reconcile his records with the MBO in relation to finding b.

We recommended and Management agreed to strengthen its management controls and ensure full implementation of its priority programs and projects that are envisioned to help achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes of the City, and require:

The City Development Council to 

Properly plan the programs and projects before inclusion in the City’s AIP. Also, prioritize development projects that are readily implementable, and during the planning stage, consider the possible problems that may be encountered in the implementation to prevent future delays;

1. Allocate additional funds to the projects with insufficient appropriations, and if it is not possible, consider implementing the projects by phase;

2. Utilized the excess funds or savings to new development programs and projects to ensure optimal utilization;

The City Engineer to

1. Fast track the identification of the new location/site for those projects which are to be relocated;

2. Resolve Right-of-Way issues to immediately commence the implementation of the projects, and to avoid future disputes;

2.1 Follow-up the Barangay Officials on the new location of the Bag-ong Lungsod Barangay Hall; 

2.2 Adhere to the target dates of implementation and find mechanisms to address unexpected situations such as quarantine protocols;

2.3 The City Planning and Development Officer to follow-up the MOA with the National Housing Authority, the partner agency;

2.4 The City Cooperative Officer to follow-up the recipient POs and cause the immediate submission of the liquidation reports, and facilitate the submission of the lacking requirements for the new release of funds; and 

2.5 The CENR Officer to take initiatives by formulating equivalent projects and programs that will also mobilize the community on the marine protected area development, such as online training or face-to-face but with limited participants.

